00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:57.760
So let's quickly recap or review functional data and functional data analysis. So we're all

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:03.920
familiar with the two major types of variables, continuous, categorical, or our usual scalar

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:10.799
approaches. Functional variables are where we can't use a single value or we don't have a single value

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:17.279
to measure the characteristic of interest, that variable for an experimental unit. So we actually

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:23.440
have an entire process, a distribution, or a curve. And so we want to be able to have a class of

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:27.359
methods that allow us to analyze functional variables. And here's some examples. These are

00:08:27.359 --> 00:08:33.200
all available in the FDA package, which all stem from Ramsey and Silverman, who are sort of the

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:38.320
original bible, I guess, of functional data analysis is the book of the same title,

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:45.200
published in the, I guess, first time in the mid-1990s. So these examples, you can find this

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:53.200
data within that package in R. And common examples, so top left, growth curves. So those of you who

00:08:53.200 --> 00:09:00.559
have children or remember going to the pediatrician as a child, right, there's unequally spaced

00:09:00.559 --> 00:09:07.200
milestone visits, but we want to track how individuals grow from birth all the way till

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:14.080
18 years. So for each person, they have an entire growth curve. The Canadian weather data, which if

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:20.799
you recall, Santiago talked about quite a bit. So for, I think it's 35 weather stations in Canada,

00:09:20.799 --> 00:09:27.359
we're looking at the temperature profile across an entire year for each of those cities and try

00:09:27.359 --> 00:09:33.760
to analyze how do the profiles differ, say, based on region in Canada. Functional data can be

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:38.799
two-dimensional or multi-dimensional. So an example is writing on an electronic pad the

00:09:38.799 --> 00:09:44.640
letters FDA in cursive multiple times. So you have this also spatial orientation. So it's not required,

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:50.400
it's rescaled to time, but, you know, it's also, you're not required to have time, say, as your

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:57.599
only dimension or your domain for your functional observation. And lastly, something that looks

00:09:57.599 --> 00:10:03.440
like distributional data, which you can see maybe some challenges in analyzing this as it has to do

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:09.359
with pinching your thumb with your forefinger and the force exerted. And so you can see that

00:10:09.359 --> 00:10:14.640
there's different time points at which the force starts and the peak force occurs at different

00:10:16.159 --> 00:10:23.760
different time values in the interval from zero to 0.3 seconds. Plus it has a different height as

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:28.559
well. So it's shifted as well as scaled. So we won't talk about it today, but registration and

00:10:28.559 --> 00:10:33.599
alignment as another pre-processing is very important for data like this. Say maybe peak

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:40.320
aligning is something you might look at. Now for analyzing functional data, there are many

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:46.960
of the methods that are just analogs to traditional scalar approaches, two which are sort of more

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:52.320
unique to functional. Well, curve estimation or smoothing. Certainly you need more than one point

00:10:53.280 --> 00:11:01.679
to smooth a curve. So that's a pre-processing step that we'll look at. I think one interesting

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:07.200
one is the analysis of derivatives. So for growth curves, you could look at acceleration functions

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:15.679
because you've now got a smooth and continuous variable observation that you can take derivatives

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:21.280
for. So you get functions, derivative functions, as opposed to just rise over run calculations.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:30.320
For the functional analogs, just so within exploratory data analysis, means, variances,

00:11:30.320 --> 00:11:35.440
correlations, you can compute all of those. You can do principal components analysis,

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:40.960
linear or generalized linear models, and you can even do functional experimental design.

00:11:41.919 --> 00:11:48.239
And many of these are related, but I think we'll see just natural extensions of methods that we

00:11:48.239 --> 00:11:56.239
know and love to apply them to functional observations. So to sort of motivate, you know,

00:11:56.239 --> 00:12:03.919
use cases for FDA. So this is our case study data that we'll talk about. Now it is simulated,

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:11.039
and in the link that Rachel, I think, sent out or will send out, I've made the slides as well

00:12:11.039 --> 00:12:18.880
as my code available. So every analysis, every picture that you see, including all the seeds,

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:25.440
is available to explore and you'll be able to reproduce everything. But for this example,

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:30.559
we have 41 different additives, different experimental materials, one of which is a

00:12:30.559 --> 00:12:35.200
standard. You can think of standard as a, it could be the gold standard on the market,

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:39.440
it could be a control, it could be just a theoretical target that you want to hit.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:46.640
So that's the solid black. But the further study on 41 different additives could be resource

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:53.280
intensive. So the idea, one of the questions we'll look at is, is how can we quickly select profiles

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:58.960
or new materials for further study that are most similar to this standard? Now,

00:13:00.479 --> 00:13:07.679
it, this material characteristic, it's measured over 24 hours, but it resembles exponential decay.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:14.400
And so as we might often see, especially with like decay functions, that this, the time points

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:20.719
at which we measure are unequally spaced. So it starts out condensed at time zero,

00:13:20.719 --> 00:13:25.599
which they all started 100. So time one, two, then it goes every two hours till eight,

00:13:25.599 --> 00:13:30.159
then every four hours till 24. So they're unequally spaced time points. And also,

00:13:30.159 --> 00:13:36.640
in the example that we had, based on the data processing to actually create these profiles,

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:42.799
we actually had a lot of missing data. So not all, actually rarely did we have all 10 points.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:50.719
So we had somewhere between five and eight points for each curve. So each observation,

00:13:50.719 --> 00:13:54.479
each material had unequally spaced points and a differing number of points.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:14:00.640
So the first question that we'll ask and try to answer, and this will be used with the functional

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:06.400
PCA is, can we pick three to five experimental materials that are top candidates for further

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:14.320
study? And second, this material characteristic, this profile is strongly related to application

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:21.119
performance. So as we try to create and design new materials, we'd say, okay, from this profile,

00:14:21.919 --> 00:14:28.400
we'd also want to know which ones to look at based on predicting performance in the final

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:33.679
application. And that's where we'll look at functional regression. Now, you might think

00:14:33.679 --> 00:14:41.280
there's, we've seen pictures like this, you know, quite often for some traditional analyses.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:45.599
So some things that we might use, maybe to not answer these exact questions, but to analyze this

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:51.440
data is you could use time series, repeated measures, longitudinal data analysis, all sort

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:57.760
of similar flavor. They answer different questions, of course, but we could do moment-based

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:04.880
regression. So try to summarize these profiles into some set of scalar moments, and then just

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:11.760
apply like typical linear models, or we could do a multivariate approach. So PCA or PLS, say,

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:17.520
if we had multiple correlated responses, and so we'd actually analyze the data matrix formed here.

00:15:18.239 --> 00:15:24.000
But each of these have some limitations. So particularly a time series repeated measures,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:30.320
typically you require equally spaced time points and the same number of points for each curve.

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:36.400
So a consistent domain for the discrete measurements. For moments, we know in dimension

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:42.799
reduction, typically we lose information. So that's always kind of a pro and con. It's easier

00:15:42.799 --> 00:15:50.960
to analyze, but we do suffer information loss. And methods like multivariates of PCA PLS,

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:56.239
well, that looks at data matrix, which kind of ignores the functional relationship between the

00:15:56.239 --> 00:16:01.840
successive columns. And in fact, with PLS, it's known, right, that if you permute the

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:06.880
columns of your data matrix, you're going to get the same model in the end. So that functional

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:14.719
relationship is essentially destroyed and are not captured in these multivariate approaches.

00:16:14.719 --> 00:16:21.119
But FDA methods allow us to alleviate or basically remove many of these limitations.

