00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:14.160
Okay. So once you have measured your functional observations, I think what you've noticed is that

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:20.400
it's not truly a smooth, continuous function that we're analyzing because we never actually

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:26.079
observe this true process because we measure it at set time points or points in the domain.

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:32.959
It's always a discretized function. So that's why smoothing is often the first step of preprocessing.

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:40.319
And in many cases, it can be a requirement for like PCA or for a functional PCA.

00:17:41.439 --> 00:17:45.760
So why do we have to do this? Well, again, with a discrete curve. So

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:51.040
X is actually our true process that we want to explore, but we actually observe Y

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:59.119
because when we go to measure the points, we try to measure at different TJs, the value of this

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:03.199
process. There's error likely involved, measurement error, process error.

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:10.079
And so we don't observe the true process. We observe something with error that we need to

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:18.800
convert to our functional observation to analyze. And so the common approaches are penalized

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:24.079
splines in some fashion, Fourier series for periodic data, cubic B-splines or some other

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:30.959
regression spline for non-periodic data. We play with the bias-variance tradeoff with a

00:18:30.959 --> 00:18:36.319
smoothing parameter lambda. And an important note is that you could do this all at once.

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.479
So you could take all your observations, smooth them all together, or you can actually

00:18:41.119 --> 00:18:45.439
treat them and do them individually, which we'll see we have to do in our case.

00:18:46.319 --> 00:18:51.119
And just to give an example of this penalization and smoothing here. So

00:18:52.079 --> 00:18:59.199
I've generated from the sine function some points. So the gray circles, I think it's 100

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:06.079
or maybe 200 points within the domain minus three to three, equally spaced. So you see that there is

00:19:06.079 --> 00:19:13.359
a process underlying this. There is a functional relationship across these points, but we don't

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:18.640
have a great, we wouldn't want to connect these points. So how do we actually estimate the true

00:19:18.719 --> 00:19:25.760
function, the black curve? So if we pick a lambda that's too small, we undersmooth. And as it

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:31.599
approaches zero, you basically interpolate the points. So you have high variance, low bias.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:39.199
So we probably wouldn't want to use that red curve. Green, if we pick a lambda too big,

00:19:39.199 --> 00:19:45.520
we oversmooth. So we actually typically will miss valleys and peaks, which you observe here.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:52.560
So here we have very low variance, but high bias. So the best is, you know, we can pick this

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:58.319
through trial and error or some cross-validation technique. But when you have an appropriately

00:19:58.319 --> 00:20:04.079
smoothed function with Fourier series, you see it's actually hard to discern the blue dashed

00:20:04.079 --> 00:20:09.680
line compared to black, which tells us that, see, we were able to use splines to capture our true,

00:20:10.479 --> 00:20:17.520
the underlying process here. Now, how does this apply to our case study data? So remember,

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:22.319
we do have the unequally spaced and differing number of points. So we'll do it individually

00:20:22.319 --> 00:20:26.560
one at a time. Remember, we only have five to eight measurements, but because of using

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:33.359
the penalized splines, we can have great flexibility with 20 cubic B-splines. So we

00:20:33.359 --> 00:20:39.280
actually have, you know, like four times as many splines as we do points, but we can still estimate

00:20:39.599 --> 00:20:45.119
the function. We do it one at a time and then reevaluate to basically form a consistent data

00:20:45.119 --> 00:20:52.079
matrix. So we fit the smooth, evaluate it at every hour time point, stack them all together. You get

00:20:52.079 --> 00:21:03.119
a 41 by 25 matrix where row per row, each row is a experimental material. And then eventually we'll

00:21:03.119 --> 00:21:09.839
kind of re-smooth or reapply the same smoothing to create a functional data object with all 41

00:21:09.839 --> 00:21:15.520
curves. So it's kind of like two different sets of smoothing. And if you check out the code,

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:21.199
you'll kind of see how this works, but we need that functional data object for later use.

00:21:21.199 --> 00:21:27.760
And how well does this work? So here's the ample for the standard. So the discrete curve is

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:32.959
actually the dashed red. Applying these splines and reevaluating and plotting, you can see that

00:21:32.959 --> 00:21:38.880
even with only, I forget how many we have on the standard, five to eight points, the smooth

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:46.719
can actually estimate that true or our underlying process very well. And we apply the same approach

00:21:46.719 --> 00:21:53.439
to all the curves. And I think you can see that we do reasonably well at capturing just the overall

00:21:53.439 --> 00:22:00.719
shape of each of those individual profiles. So now the question becomes, how do we address the

00:22:00.719 --> 00:22:08.479
two questions? So I guess a short section, if there are any questions, we can take them on

00:22:08.479 --> 00:22:17.119
